ging conflict to a close? Keen asks who benefits from wars--whether economically, politically, or psychologically-and argues that in order to bring them successfully to an end we need to understand the complex vested interests on all sides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPolitics and war. 0aProtracted conflicts (Military science). 0aViolencexSocial aspects. 0aWar crimes. 0aWarxCauses. 0aWarxPsychological aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030016274540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018371940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300183719423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300183719/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY